---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Sanshin Day: Why Okinawa Stops Everything on March 4th | Unmuting Ryukyu">

	<article>

		<!-- ARTICLE HEADER -->
		<header style="padding:72px 32px 56px;background:#1C2C4F;position:relative;overflow:hidden;border-bottom:4px solid #8B1D25;">
			<div style="position:absolute;inset:-15px;z-index:0;background-image:url('https://img.youtube.com/vi/5Ng56rsjb4E/maxresdefault.jpg');background-size:cover;background-position:center;filter:blur(6px);opacity:0.25;"></div>
			<div style="position:absolute;inset:0;z-index:0;background:#1C2C4F;opacity:0.78;"></div>
			<div style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;width:5px;height:100%;background:#8B1D25;z-index:2;"></div>
			<div style="max-width:840px;margin:0 auto;position:relative;z-index:2;">
				<div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:12px;margin-bottom:20px;">
					<span style="display:inline-block;background:#8B1D25;color:#F0EBE3;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;padding:4px 12px;letter-spacing:0.1em;text-transform:uppercase;">Okinawan Culture</span>
					<span style="color:#8B9BB8;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:12px;">March 2026</span>
				</div>
				<h1 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:clamp(26px,5vw,44px);font-weight:700;color:#F0EBE3;margin:0 0 20px 0;line-height:1.25;">Sanshin Day: Why Okinawa Stops Everything on March 4th</h1>
				<p style="color:#C8A86A;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:15px;font-style:italic;margin:0 0 16px 0;line-height:1.7;">Every year, at 3:04 PM, thousands of Okinawans pick up their instruments simultaneously — a living act of cultural defiance and pride.</p>
				<p style="color:#8B9BB8;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:13px;margin:0;">By <a href="/about/" style="color:#D4C9BC;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Shohei Toguchi</a></p>
			</div>
		</header>

		<!-- ARTICLE BODY -->
		<div style="padding:72px 32px 96px;background:#F0EBE3;">
			<div style="max-width:720px;margin:0 auto;">

				<!-- Opening pull quote -->
				<div style="border-left:4px solid #8B1D25;padding:24px 32px;margin-bottom:56px;background:#fff;">
					<p style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:20px;color:#1C2C4F;line-height:1.7;margin:0;font-style:italic;">"3 (san) — 4 (shi/shin). March 4th. The date itself is the instrument's name."</p>
				</div>

				<!-- Article Content -->
				<div style="font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;color:#4A3F3B;font-size:16px;line-height:1.95;">

					<h2 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 20px 0;padding-top:8px;border-top:2px solid #D0C5BA;">What is Sanshin Day?</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						Every year on March 4th, Okinawa observes <strong>三線の日 (Sanshin no Hi)</strong> — Sanshin Day. The date is a wordplay: in Japanese, "3" can be read as <em>san</em>, and "4" as <em>shi</em> or <em>shin</em>. Put them together and you get <em>sanshin</em> — the name of Okinawa's most beloved instrument.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						The tradition began in 1993, organized by Okinawa's broadcasting and music communities. At exactly 3:04 PM, radio stations across the islands broadcast a live sanshin performance, and anyone who owns one — or is near one — is invited to play along. Simultaneously.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 40px 0;">
						It is not a performance. It is not a concert. It is a declaration.
					</p>

					<h2 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 20px 0;padding-top:8px;border-top:2px solid #D0C5BA;">What Is the Sanshin?</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 20px 0;">
						The sanshin is a three-stringed lute — the heart of Ryukyuan music. At its core, it is deceptively simple: a long wooden neck, a small rounded body covered in python skin, and three silk or nylon strings. But its sound is unmistakable — ancient, aching, and alive.
					</p>

					<!-- Instrument facts -->
					<div style="display:grid;gap:2px;background:#D0C5BA;margin-bottom:40px;">
						<div style="background:#fff;padding:24px 28px;display:grid;grid-template-columns:100px 1fr;gap:16px;align-items:start;">
							<p style="font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#8B1D25;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.15em;margin:0;">Origin</p>
							<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-size:15px;line-height:1.8;margin:0;">Derived from the Chinese <em>sanxian</em>, adapted in the Ryukyu Kingdom (14th–15th century) into a distinct Okinawan form.</p>
						</div>
						<div style="background:#fff;padding:24px 28px;display:grid;grid-template-columns:100px 1fr;gap:16px;align-items:start;">
							<p style="font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#8B1D25;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.15em;margin:0;">Body</p>
							<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-size:15px;line-height:1.8;margin:0;">Traditionally covered in python skin (<em>jabisen</em>), giving it its distinctive warm, textured tone. Modern versions use synthetic skin.</p>
						</div>
						<div style="background:#fff;padding:24px 28px;display:grid;grid-template-columns:100px 1fr;gap:16px;align-items:start;">
							<p style="font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#8B1D25;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.15em;margin:0;">Played with</p>
							<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-size:15px;line-height:1.8;margin:0;">A large plectrum called <em>bachi</em>, worn on the index finger, striking downward with authority and grace.</p>
						</div>
						<div style="background:#fff;padding:24px 28px;display:grid;grid-template-columns:100px 1fr;gap:16px;align-items:start;">
							<p style="font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#8B1D25;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.15em;margin:0;">Relation to</p>
							<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-size:15px;line-height:1.8;margin:0;">The Japanese <em>shamisen</em> — the sanshin traveled from Okinawa to mainland Japan, where it evolved into a separate tradition.</p>
						</div>
					</div>

					<h2 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 20px 0;padding-top:8px;border-top:2px solid #D0C5BA;">Why March 4th Matters More Than You Think</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						Okinawa has been silenced — repeatedly, and by force. The Ryukyu Kingdom was absorbed into Japan in 1879. The Okinawan language (<em>Uchinaaguchi</em>) was suppressed in schools. The Battle of Okinawa in 1945 devastated an entire generation. Post-war American occupation lasted until 1972.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						Through all of it, the sanshin survived. Not in museums — in living rooms, on fishing boats, at village festivals. People hid their instruments. They played in secret. They taught their children anyway.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 40px 0;">
						Sanshin Day is not just a cultural celebration. It is an annual reminder that Okinawa is still here — still playing, still singing, still refusing to disappear.
					</p>

					<!-- Highlight box -->
					<div style="background:#1C2C4F;padding:36px 40px;margin-bottom:40px;position:relative;overflow:hidden;">
						<div style="position:absolute;right:-20px;bottom:-30px;font-family:'Shippori Mincho',serif;font-size:120px;font-weight:700;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.04);line-height:1;user-select:none;">三線</div>
						<p style="color:#C8A86A;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 16px 0;">Did You Know?</p>
						<p style="color:#F0EBE3;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:16px;line-height:1.85;margin:0;">The sanshin was designated an <strong style="color:#C8A86A;">Intangible Cultural Asset</strong> by Okinawa Prefecture. Today, it is estimated that there are over <strong style="color:#C8A86A;">300,000 sanshin players</strong> in Okinawa — a prefecture with a population of only 1.4 million.</p>
					</div>

					<h2 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 20px 0;padding-top:8px;border-top:2px solid #D0C5BA;">How to Experience Sanshin Day</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 20px 0;">
						If you are in Okinawa on March 4th, here is what to expect:
					</p>

					<div style="background:#fff;border-left:4px solid #8B1D25;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px;">
						<p style="color:#8B1D25;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.15em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 8px 0;">3:04 PM — The Simultaneous Play</p>
						<p style="color:#1C2C4F;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:15px;line-height:1.85;margin:0;">RBC Radio broadcasts a live performance. Tune in, pick up a sanshin if you have one, or simply stop and listen. Across the island, thousands of people are playing the same melody at the same moment.</p>
					</div>
					<div style="background:#fff;border-left:4px solid #1C2C4F;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px;">
						<p style="color:#1C2C4F;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.15em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 8px 0;">Live Events Around the Island</p>
						<p style="color:#1C2C4F;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:15px;line-height:1.85;margin:0;">Community halls, parks, and shopping areas host open sanshin sessions. No ticket required. Any skill level welcome. The point is participation, not performance.</p>
					</div>
					<div style="background:#fff;border-left:4px solid #8B1D25;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:40px;">
						<p style="color:#8B1D25;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.15em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 8px 0;">Can't Be There? Join Online</p>
						<p style="color:#1C2C4F;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:15px;line-height:1.85;margin:0;">In recent years, Sanshin Day has gone global. Uchinanchu communities in Hawaii, Brazil, and across Japan stream the broadcast and play together online. You don't have to be in Okinawa to participate — you just have to care.</p>
					</div>

					<h2 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 20px 0;padding-top:8px;border-top:2px solid #D0C5BA;">The Sound of a Culture Unmuted</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						There is a specific feeling when you hear the sanshin for the first time. Something opens. It is not quite melancholy, not quite joy — it sits in the space between loss and survival, which is exactly where Okinawan culture lives.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						The instrument's three strings carry centuries. The <em>bachi</em> strikes down and the note rings out — clear, then trailing off into a resonance that feels older than memory.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0;">
						That is what 300,000 people play together on March 4th. Not a song. A signal. <em>We are still here.</em>
					</p>

				</div>

